    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-05-14T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-05-14T12:00:00-05:00" n="774"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d774">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.119/315a suppl.: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Tenney</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-05-14T13:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 14, 1920—1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>116. Supplementing Department’s No. 91 April 23rd noon to which reply is awaited.
                    The Department is further informed that <pb facs="0841" n="743" xml:id="pg_743"
                    /> in addition to Belgian consignment of arms delivered at Tientsin there have
                    been delivered to a Chinese arsenal from Great Britain steel materials for the
                    manufacture of munitions. Report by telegraph whether you consider that
                    complaints of violation of embargo by Belgian, British, Italian, and Japanese
                    interests are well founded.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
